 combined her talents for teaching and stitchery to inspire and instruct a new generation in the demanding art form. Together with her husband, Yoshio, who created the distinctive, eye-catching designs used by hers students, Ima Shimoda was responsible for not only furthering the practice of shishu in Hawai'i but ensuring its existence as a vital link for many nisei to their cultural past and its traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEmbroideryzJapan. 0aJapanese American womenzHawaiixSocial conditions. 0aWomen artisanszHawaiivCase studies. 7aCRAFTS & HOBBIES / Needlework / Embroidery.2bisacsh1 aNunes-Atabaki, Sara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486503040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824865030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824865030/original  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK